Use tidyr::uncount() function to convert our lobster data from frequency format to case format

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>%
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

# uncount makes it easy to get from frequency to case format. Will increase number of observations and get rid of column that you uncounted. Use complete_cases() to retrieve values for zero counts so that you still have those observations in your data frame.

Exploratory data visualization

Were only going to consider site as our variable of interest

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site),
              alpha = 0.5,
              width = 0.2)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# Histogram 
ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

# all grouped together and R has no idea that these are different groups, so make fill = site and facet_wrap so that each site is their own graph. Keep scales of graphs the same so that comparisons can easily be made. If you don't care about comparing across graphs, then you can change the scale (use scales = "free")

# Quantile-Quantile
ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(sample = size_mm)) +
  geom_qq() +
  facet_wrap(~site)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_qq).

# with quantile-quantile, you don't list x & y, you just list your sample. Overall, this looks like a linear relationship (not counting about 6 observations). These lobster data are close to normally distributed. Use facet_wrap to graph data by site.

Convert the date column to class Date

Well use the lubridate package to convert to Date format, and then to help us easily parse month and year

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>%
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

# automatically puts date in YYYY-MM-DD

Now lets parse year and month using lubridate::month() and lubridate::year()

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>%
  mutate(
    obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
    obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new)
  )

# default is to pull the month number for lubradte::month(). To have the month abbreviation show up, use label = TRUE, will parse month by number but then replace that with abbreviation.

Now lets find counts of observed lobsters based on different hierarchical groupings:

First, lets count lobsters by year and month:

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>%

If we want to create a summary table that contains statistics OTHER than counts by group, its easier to use group_by() + n()

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>%
  group_by(site) %>%
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    lobster_number = n()
  )

lobster_summary
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   site  mean_size sd_size lobster_number
##   <chr>     <dbl>   <dbl>          <int>
## 1 AQUE       72.3    11.4            422
## 2 CARP       72.8    12.5           1619
## 3 IVEE       73.6    14.4           2304
## 4 MOHK       66.9    14.2            982
## 5 NAPL       78.2    11.1           1039

Find confidence intervals

Use t.test() function to find confidence intervals (for one sample) and perform t-tests to compare means of two samples (this will be covered conceptually in lectures week 6)

ivee_lobster <- lobster_tidy %>%
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>%
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobster)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobster
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

Two-sample t-test to compare means

We want to ask: is there a significant difference in lobster length at Naples and Mohawk reefs?

Weve done our necessary exploratory analyses to determine that a 2-sample t-test for means comparison is appropriate.

naples_sample <- lobster_tidy %>%
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>%
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>%
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>%
  pull(size_mm)

mn_ttest <- t.test(mohk_sample, naples_sample)
mn_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mohk_sample and naples_sample
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  66.86833  78.18454
# default of t.test function "in either direction, are these significantly different?"

There is a significant difference in lobster lengths between Naples and Mohawk Reef (t(df)) = statistic, p < 0.001, alpha = 0.05).

lobster_mn <- lobster_tidy %>%
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL", "MOHK"))



mn_ttest2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_mn)

mn_ttest2
